Prolog
“I beg you!”, Queen Eirwen implored, “Don’t send her away! She is still a child!” The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his gaze darkened.
The girl resembled her mother greatly. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, he had fathered only sons up to this point.
“You have two options: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is its punishment for your failure, Eirwen.” He spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He did that always.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, in the South a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and it came to an endless war between the two kingdoms, until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the south was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as a queen to the north, where she would bear a son, the future king. In this case, the north would unite with the south into a kingdom. The north accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
“I beg of you, my king, do with me as you wish, imprison me, exile me, or kill me, but spare my child,” begged Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms,”
The Ice King looked down on his queen with contempt. Maybe, but only maybe, he would show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his darkest times and had given him his sons.
“Fine. The child can stay in the palace,” he said, which was noted by the queen with a sigh. “But,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the ground. “Yes, my king.” She bowed down.
The Ice King instructed the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's free rooms. Subsequently, he ordered the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution site, where all citizens of the city could watch.
While the guards escorted her to the execution site, it was amidst the citizens that a loud disturbance arose, as they understood that their only, beloved queen was to be executed. Some people cried, others shouted and attacked the guards. Yet others wondered why this was happening, but everyone was in agreement.
“Let them go!”
“Why are they being done this to?”
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Brand Judge. The woman who was still queen just a moment ago, was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even a criminal. It was the most terrifying thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the wooden stake, and the King declared in a speech how the Queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the King and did not want to accept his words. Then the Executioner of Fires lit the wooden stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former Queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of the reign of Queen Eirwen.
Silence of the Dead in the Palace
Only a knocking was heard from the room located to the far left in the south wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by wondered what was in the room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors spread among the maids. Allegedly, the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and waiting to be let out.
Her speculation could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory and headed towards the south wing, while the staff went about and whispered to each other. They had no idea what was behind the door.
The rumors naturally also concerned Ivory, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?", Ivory whispered before the door decorated with snowflakes and a crown, symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if – unlike the last attempt – actual entry would be granted this time. I still have blue bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, apologized immediately when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock was heard from inside, probably to indicate that she was there. Where else would she be?
"May I enter?", Ivory asked. In the past, Ivory had entered without asking.
Aus dem Inneren vernahm Ivory ein Klopfen. Das bedeutete wohl ein „Ja“. Die Kälte und das Geräusch ließen Ivory erschauern. Es fühlte sich komisch an, ein Geräusch aus einem angeblich leeren Zimmer zu hören, obwohl Ivory schon seit einigen Jahren dort hineinging.
„Ich komme rein“, sagte Ivory und öffnete langsam die Tür. Der Anblick, der sich Ivory in dem Raum bot, war für normale Menschen ungewöhnlich, kam für Ivory aber nicht unerwartet. Überall lag Papier. Bücher waren verstreut, der Schreibtisch war zerbrochen und mehrere Eisskulpturen lagen herum. Es gab keine Fenster und wenig bis gar kein Licht. Außerdem war es kälter als im restlichen Palast (was schon einiges sagte). Der Raum sah aus, als sei ein Schneesturm hindurch gefegt.
Das Mädchen lag zusammengerollt in ihrem Bett, eingewickelt in ihre Bettdecke, und las in einem ihrer Notizbücher. Eine kleine Laterne erhellte den Raum.
„Welches Notizbuch ist das?“, fragte Ivory und setzte sich neben Kari aufs Bett.
